               <msContents>
                  <summary>A second, probably complete volume of <title>‘Ayn al-Ḥayat</title> (Eye of Life), a major Persian Shi’ite work on
                     theology and ethics by Muhammad Baqir ibn Muḥammad Taqī Majlisī (ca.
                     1628–1700).</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_507-item1">
                     <author key="person_90076153" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/90076153/">
                        <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Majlisī, Muḥammad Bāqir
                           ibn Muḥammad Taqī, 1627 or 8-ca. 1699 <foreign xml:lang="fa">مجلسى، محمد
                              باقر بن محمد تقى</foreign>
                        </persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_6995">ʻAyn al-Ḥayāt</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_6995">عين الحياة</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="ar" type="beginnig"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio
                           1b):</locus> پرسید که کیست که جفاکار تراست(،) گفت پادشاه ظالم و دلی که در
                        آن رحم نباشدپرسید که چه چیز است که به نهایت نمیرسد، گفت که چشم صاحب حرص که
                        هرگزاز دنیا سیر نمیشود... ،</incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa">
                        <locus from="424b" to="424b">424b</locus> باینجا ختم میکنم کتاب عین
                        ...الحیوة را</explicit>
                     <colophon>No colophon</colophon>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note>The order of the contents in this volume varies from other volumes.
                        Following the conclusion of Volume I, Volume II opens abruptly. The title
                        appears therein towards the end on <locus from="424b" to="424b"
                        >424b</locus>. The beginning of the text corresponds to middle of <hi
                           rend="italic">Bāb</hi> 2 of <hi rend="italic">Samarah</hi> 3 and the
                        first heading on <locus from="34a" to="34a">34a</locus>, for <hi
                           rend="italic">Bāb</hi> 3 (باب سیوم در بیان معنی دنیاست), corresponds with
                        Cambridge University Library Add. 3153, folio 127a. See Browne catalogue.
                        For printed editions, see Mushār.</note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>The initial majority of the textblock on folios <locus from="1a"
                              to="305b">1a to 305b</locus> comprised of cross-grained, externally
                           sized and polished, ivoury-coloured <material>paper</material> probably
                           handmade in the <placeName cert="high"
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208"
                              >Indian subcontinent</placeName> with ~8 laid lines per cm and no
                           discernible chain lines. Folios <locus from="306a" to="424b">306a to
                              424b</locus> of straight and cross-grained ivory-coloured externally
                           sized and polished paper, probably also handmade in the <placeName
                              cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                              key="place_7000208">Indian subcontinent</placeName>, with ~8 laid
                           lines per cm and no discernible chain lines.</support>
                        <extent><measure quantity="424" unit="folio">424 folios, 2 fly leaves (ff. i
                              + 424 + i)</measure>. <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>2436</height>
                              <width>146</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>184</height>
                              <width>87</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation xml:id="modern">Partially foliated in Arabic numerals</foliation>
                        <collation>Undertermined. <catchwords>Catchwords present on the lower-left corners of the b sides throughout.</catchwords></collation>
                        <condition>Handle text with caution. Initial, original portion on folios
                              <locus from="1a" to="305b">1a to 305b</locus> in poor condition, with
                           etensive discolouration, insect damage, and historical repairs, while
                           replaced folios <locus from="306a" to="424b">306a to 424b</locus> appear
                           in better condition. </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" writtenLines="12">Written in 1 column with 12 lines per
                           page. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq" medium="ink">Written in black
                        nasta‘līq with overlinings in red.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <lb/>
                     <label>Marginalia:</label> notations in the margins in various hands throughout.<lb/>
                     <label>Inscriptions</label> the <locus from="ia" to="ia">first right flyleaf a
                        side (f. ia)</locus> bears the title and name of former owner <persName
                        type="supplied" key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment"
                        >Colonel George William Hamilton </persName>, likely in the bold black
                     nasta‘līq hand of his assistant <persName role="wst" key="person_f6587">Muhīn
                        Dās</persName>:<lb/>
                     <q xml:lang="fa">علم کلام: جلد دویم عین الحیوة تالیف محمد باقر بن محمد تقی:
                        بیان حدیث<lb/> كرنل جارج وليم هميلتن صاحب بهادر</q><lb/>
                     <label>Bookplates:</label> The <locus from="Inner_back_cover"
                        to="Inner_back_cover">left doublure</locus>: <q xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca
                        Lindesiana</q> with pencilled shelfmark <q xml:lang="en">2/G</q>, and <q
                        xml:lang="en"><hi rend="strikethrough">Hamilton</hi> MSS No. <hi
                           rend="strikethrough">424</hi></q>, with the name and number crossed out
                     and <q xml:lang="en">Persian</q> and <q xml:lang="en">507</q> written aside. </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1862" notAfter="1867">
                        <p>Probably rebound in <placeName
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535" key="place_7001535">
                              Dehli</placeName> between <date calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1862"
                              notAfter="1867">1862 to 1867</date> for former owner <persName
                              type="supplied" key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment"
                              >Colonel George William Hamilton </persName>.</p>
                        <p>Resewn on a single support, with comparatively heavy stock added as the
                           first and least flyleaves. Edges trimmed and chevron endbands twined in
                           yellow and silk threads over round cores as <locus from="Head" to="Head">head</locus> and
                              <locus from="Tail" to="Tail">tail</locus>. Covered in full maroon
                           goatskin <material>leather</material> over pasteboards, with with
                           internal doublures lined in the same, with squares along the edges,
                           defined joints, but without a flap (type III binding per Déroche).</p>
                        <decoNote type="binding">Boards decorated with green paper blind-stamped
                           onlays featuring scalloped central mandorlas, detached pendants, and
                           corners, with board margins stained dark brown about ~1cm in from the
                           edges, as well as the spine. Spine bears an octagonal paper label with the title of the work written in nasta‘līq. </decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>255</height>
                              <width>161</width>
                              <depth>55</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Binding in good condition, with som abrasion to the exterior, whitened salts on the interior resulting from prolonged exposure to moisture, and opening to the gutter margins
                           restricted.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p>Folio <locus from="305b" to="305b">305b</locus> bears a single
                           rectanglular black seal impression featuring an oval laurel wreath with
                           the name of former owner or associate <persName role="fmo asn seal">Mīrzā Āghā
                              Khān</persName>, possibly dated <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                              from="1823" to="1824">1229 AH (1823–24 CE)</date>.<lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>13</height>
                              <width>15</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </p>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>Possibly completed in the <origPlace cert="medium"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208">Indian
                        subcontinent</origPlace>
                     <origDate cert="medium" calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1700" notAfter="1800"
                        >possibly 18th century</origDate>.</origin>

                  <provenance><p>Subsequently inspected or owned by one <persName role="fmo asn seal">Mīrzā Āghā
                     Khān</persName> as per his seal, possibly dated <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                        from="1823" to="1824">1229 AH (1823–24 CE)</date>, on folio <locus from="305b" to="305b">305b</locus></p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>
                     Subsequently acquired by <persName type="supplied" key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Colonel George William Hamilton (1807-1868)</persName> 
                     who served in <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208">India</placeName> <date calendar="#Gregorian" from="1823" to="1867"> from 1823 to 1867</date>, latterly as Commissioner in <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535" key="place_7001535">Delhi</placeName>. 
                     He acquired over a thousand Indian and Persian manuscripts, from which the
                     <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/134857252">British Museum</orgName> purchased 352 from his widow, now held in the
                     <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/121814978">British Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </provenance> 
                  <provenance><p>
                     <persName role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058">
                        Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName> purchased  the remainder of Hamilton's collection in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1868">1868</date>.
                  </p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName role="dnr" key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup"
                     >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                        when="1901">1901</date> from <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands
                        (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908"
                           >1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands
                              Library</orgName>, <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477"
                                 key="place_7010477">Manchester</placeName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>                     <additional>
